14_3_3	14-3-3 homologues	SM00101	14-3-3 homologues mediates signal transduction by binding to phosphoserine-containing proteins. They are involved in growth factor signalling and also interact with MEK kinases.
4.1m	putative band 4.1 homologues' binding motif	SM00294	-
acidPPc	Acid phosphatase homologues	SM00014	-
ADF	Actin depolymerisation factor/cofilin -like domains	SM00102	Severs actin filaments and binds to actin monomers.
ANK	ankyrin repeats	SM00248	Ankyrin repeats are about 33 amino acids long and occur in at least four consecutive copies. They are involved in protein-protein interactions. The core of the repeat seems to be an helix-loop-helix structure.
APCDDC	Adenomatosis polyposis coli down-regulated 1	SM01352	The domain is duplicated in most members of this family. APCDD is directly regulated by the beta-catenin/Tcf complex, and its elevated expression promotes proliferation of colonic epithelial cells in vitro and in vivo (PMID:12384519). APCDD1 has an N-terminal signal-peptide and a C-terminal transmembrane region. The domain is rich in cysteines, there being up to 12 such residues, a structural motif important for interaction between Wnt ligands and their receptors. APCDD1 is expressed in a broad repertoire of cell types, indicating that it may regulate a diverse range of biological processes controlled by Wnt signalling (PMID:20393562).
ARF	-like small GTPases; , ADP-ribosylation factor	SM00177	Ras homologues involved in vesicular transport. Activator of phospholipase D isoforms. Unlike Ras proteins they lack cysteine residues at their C-termini and therefore are unlikely to be prenylated. ARFs are N-terminally myristoylated. Contains ATP/GTP-binding motif (P-loop).
ArfGap	Putative GTP-ase activating proteins for the small GTPase, ARF	SM00105	Putative zinc fingers with GTPase activating proteins (GAPs) towards the small GTPase, Arf. The GAP of ARD1 stimulates GTPase hydrolysis for ARD1 but not ARFs.
ARM	Armadillo/beta-catenin-like repeats	SM00185	Approx. 40 amino acid repeat. Tandem repeats form superhelix of helices that is proposed to mediate interaction of beta-catenin with its ligands. Involved in transducing the Wingless/Wnt signal. In plakoglobin arm repeats bind alpha-catenin and N-cadherin.
B41	Band 4.1 homologues	SM00295	Also known as ezrin/radixin/moesin (ERM) protein domains. Present in myosins, ezrin, radixin, moesin, protein tyrosine phosphatases. Plasma membrane-binding domain. These proteins play structural and regulatory roles in the assembly and stabilization of specialized plasmamembrane domains. Some PDZ domain containing proteins bind one or more of this family. Now includes JAKs.
B561	Cytochrome b-561 / ferric reductase transmembrane domain.	SM00665	Cytochrome b-561 recycles ascorbate for the generation of norepinephrine by dopamine-beta-hydroxylase in the chromaffin vesicles of the adrenal gland. It is a transmembrane heme protein with the two heme groups being bound to conserved histidine residues. A cytochrome b-561 homologue, termed Dcytb, is an iron-regulated ferric reductase in the duodenal mucosa. Other homologues of these are also likely to be ferric reductases. SDR2 is proposed to be important in regulating the metabolism of iron in the onset of neurodegenerative disorders.
B_lectin	Bulb-type mannose-specific lectin	SM00108	-
BAG	domains, present in regulator of Hsp70 proteins	SM00264	BAG domains, present in Bcl-2-associated athanogene 1 and silencer of death domains
BH4	Bcl-2 homology region 4	SM00265	-
BIR	Baculoviral inhibition of apoptosis protein repeat	SM00238	Domain found in inhibitor of apoptosis proteins (IAPs) and other proteins. Acts as a direct inhibitor of caspase enzymes.
BTK	Bruton's tyrosine kinase Cys-rich motif	SM00107	Zinc-binding motif containing conserved cysteines and a histidine. Always found C-terminal to PH domains (but not all PH domains are followed by BTK motifs). The crystal structure shows this motif packs against the PH domain. The PH+Btk module pair has been called the Tec homology (TH) region.
C1	Protein kinase C conserved region 1 () domains (Cysteine-rich domains)	SM00109	Some bind phorbol esters and diacylglycerol. Some bind RasGTP. Zinc-binding domains.
C2	Protein kinase C conserved region 2 (CalB)	SM00239	Ca2+-binding motif present in phospholipases, protein kinases C, and synaptotagmins (among others). Some do not appear to contain Ca2+-binding sites. Particular C2s appear to bind phospholipids, inositol polyphosphates, and intracellular proteins. Unusual occurrence in perforin. Synaptotagmin and PLC C2s are permuted in sequence with respect to N- and C-terminal beta strands. SMART detects C2 domains using one or both of two profiles.
Calx_beta	Domains in Na-Ca exchangers and integrin-beta4	SM00237	Domain in Na-Ca exchangers and integrin subunit beta4 (and some cyanobacterial proteins)
CARD	Caspase recruitment domain	SM00114	Motif contained in proteins involved in apoptotic signalling. Mediates homodimerisation. Structure consists of six antiparallel helices arranged in a topology homologue to the DEATH and the DED domain.
CASc	Caspase, interleukin-1 beta converting enzyme (ICE) homologues	SM00115	Cysteine aspartases that mediate programmed cell death (apoptosis). Caspases are synthesised as zymogens and activated by proteolysis of the peptide backbone adjacent to an aspartate. The resulting two subunits associate to form an (alpha)2(beta)2-tetramer which is the active enzyme. Activation of caspases can be mediated by other caspase homologues.
CH	Calponin homology domain	SM00033	Actin binding domains present in duplicate at the N-termini of spectrin-like proteins (including dystrophin, alpha-actinin). These domains cross-link actin filaments into bundles and networks. A calponin homology domain is predicted in yeasst Cdc24p.
CheW	Two component signalling adaptor domain	SM00260	-
CNH	Domain found in NIK1-like kinases, mouse citron and yeast ROM1, ROM2	SM00036	Unpublished observations.
cNMP	Cyclic nucleotide-monophosphate binding domain	SM00100	Catabolite gene activator protein (CAP) is a prokaryotic homologue of eukaryotic cNMP-binding domains, present in ion channels, and cNMP-dependent kinases.
CULLIN	Cullin	SM00182	-
CYCc	Adenylyl- / guanylyl cyclase, catalytic domain	SM00044	Present in two copies in mammalian adenylyl cyclases. Eubacterial homologues are known. Two residues (Asn, Arg) are thought to be involved in catalysis. These cyclases have important roles in a diverse range of cellular processes.
Cyclin_C	N/A	SM01332	Cyclins are a family of proteins that control the progression of cells through the cell cycle by activating cyclin-dependent kinase (Cdk) enzymes.
Cyt-b5	Cytochrome b5-like Heme/Steroid binding domain	SM01117	This family includes heme binding domains from a diverse range of proteins. This family also includes proteins that bind to steroids. The family includes progesterone receptors such as O00264 ((PUBMED:9705155),(PUBMED:8774719)). Many members of this subfamily are membrane anchored by an N-terminal transmembrane alpha helix. This family also includes a domain in some chitin synthases. There is no known ligand for this domain in the chitin synthases.
DAGKa	Diacylglycerol kinase accessory domain (presumed)	SM00045	Diacylglycerol (DAG) is a second messenger that acts as a protein kinase C activator. DAG can be produced from the hydrolysis of phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) by a phosphoinositide-specific phospholipase C and by the degradation of phosphatidylcholine (PC) by a phospholipase C or the concerted actions of phospholipase D and phosphatidate phosphohydrolase. This domain might either be an accessory domain or else contribute to the catalytic domain. Bacterial homologues are known.

gt:
title	subtitle	smart_accession_number	description
14_3_3	14-3-3 homologues	SM00101	14-3-3 homologues mediates signal transduction by binding to phosphoserine-containing proteins. They are involved in growth factor signalling and also interact with MEK kinases.
ADF	Actin depolymerisation factor/cofilin -like domains	SM00102	Severs actin filaments and binds to actin monomers.
ANK	ankyrin repeats	SM00248	Ankyrin repeats are about 33 amino acids long and occur in at least four consecutive copies. They are involved in protein-protein interactions. The core of the repeat seems to be an helix-loop-helix structure.
APCDDC	Adenomatosis polyposis coli down-regulated 1	SM01352	The domain is duplicated in most members of this family. APCDD is directly regulated by the beta-catenin/Tcf complex, and its elevated expression promotes proliferation of colonic epithelial cells in vitro and in vivo (PMID:12384519). APCDD1 has an N-terminal signal-peptide and a C-terminal transmembrane region. The domain is rich in cysteines, there being up to 12 such residues, a structural motif important for interaction between Wnt ligands and their receptors. APCDD1 is expressed in a broad repertoire of cell types, indicating that it may regulate a diverse range of biological processes controlled by Wnt signalling (PMID:20393562).
ARF	-like small GTPases; , ADP-ribosylation factor	SM00177	Ras homologues involved in vesicular transport. Activator of phospholipase D isoforms. Unlike Ras proteins they lack cysteine residues at their C-termini and therefore are unlikely to be prenylated. ARFs are N-terminally myristoylated. Contains ATP/GTP-binding motif (P-loop).
ArfGap	Putative GTP-ase activating proteins for the small GTPase, ARF	SM00105	Putative zinc fingers with GTPase activating proteins (GAPs) towards the small GTPase, Arf. The GAP of ARD1 stimulates GTPase hydrolysis for ARD1 but not ARFs.
ARM	Armadillo/beta-catenin-like repeats	SM00185	Approx. 40 amino acid repeat. Tandem repeats form superhelix of helices that is proposed to mediate interaction of beta-catenin with its ligands. Involved in transducing the Wingless/Wnt signal. In plakoglobin arm repeats bind alpha-catenin and N-cadherin.
B41	Band 4.1 homologues	SM00295	Also known as ezrin/radixin/moesin (ERM) protein domains. Present in myosins, ezrin, radixin, moesin, protein tyrosine phosphatases. Plasma membrane-binding domain. These proteins play structural and regulatory roles in the assembly and stabilization of specialized plasmamembrane domains. Some PDZ domain containing proteins bind one or more of this family. Now includes JAKs.
B561	Cytochrome b-561 / ferric reductase transmembrane domain.	SM00665	Cytochrome b-561 recycles ascorbate for the generation of norepinephrine by dopamine-beta-hydroxylase in the chromaffin vesicles of the adrenal gland. It is a transmembrane heme protein with the two heme groups being bound to conserved histidine residues. A cytochrome b-561 homologue, termed Dcytb, is an iron-regulated ferric reductase in the duodenal mucosa. Other homologues of these are also likely to be ferric reductases. SDR2 is proposed to be important in regulating the metabolism of iron in the onset of neurodegenerative disorders.
BAG	domains, present in regulator of Hsp70 proteins	SM00264	BAG domains, present in Bcl-2-associated athanogene 1 and silencer of death domains
BIR	Baculoviral inhibition of apoptosis protein repeat	SM00238	Domain found in inhibitor of apoptosis proteins (IAPs) and other proteins. Acts as a direct inhibitor of caspase enzymes.
BTK	Bruton's tyrosine kinase Cys-rich motif	SM00107	Zinc-binding motif containing conserved cysteines and a histidine. Always found C-terminal to PH domains (but not all PH domains are followed by BTK motifs). The crystal structure shows this motif packs against the PH domain. The PH+Btk module pair has been called the Tec homology (TH) region.
C1	Protein kinase C conserved region 1 () domains (Cysteine-rich domains)	SM00109	Some bind phorbol esters and diacylglycerol. Some bind RasGTP. Zinc-binding domains.
C2	Protein kinase C conserved region 2 (CalB)	SM00239	Ca2+-binding motif present in phospholipases, protein kinases C, and synaptotagmins (among others). Some do not appear to contain Ca2+-binding sites. Particular C2s appear to bind phospholipids, inositol polyphosphates, and intracellular proteins. Unusual occurrence in perforin. Synaptotagmin and PLC C2s are permuted in sequence with respect to N- and C-terminal beta strands. SMART detects C2 domains using one or both of two profiles.
Calx_beta	Domains in Na-Ca exchangers and integrin-beta4	SM00237	Domain in Na-Ca exchangers and integrin subunit beta4 (and some cyanobacterial proteins)
CARD	Caspase recruitment domain	SM00114	Motif contained in proteins involved in apoptotic signalling. Mediates homodimerisation. Structure consists of six antiparallel helices arranged in a topology homologue to the DEATH and the DED domain.
CASc	Caspase, interleukin-1 beta converting enzyme (ICE) homologues	SM00115	Cysteine aspartases that mediate programmed cell death (apoptosis). Caspases are synthesised as zymogens and activated by proteolysis of the peptide backbone adjacent to an aspartate. The resulting two subunits associate to form an (alpha)2(beta)2-tetramer which is the active enzyme. Activation of caspases can be mediated by other caspase homologues.
CH	Calponin homology domain	SM00033	Actin binding domains present in duplicate at the N-termini of spectrin-like proteins (including dystrophin, alpha-actinin). These domains cross-link actin filaments into bundles and networks. A calponin homology domain is predicted in yeasst Cdc24p.
CNH	Domain found in NIK1-like kinases, mouse citron and yeast ROM1, ROM2	SM00036	Unpublished observations.
cNMP	Cyclic nucleotide-monophosphate binding domain	SM00100	Catabolite gene activator protein (CAP) is a prokaryotic homologue of eukaryotic cNMP-binding domains, present in ion channels, and cNMP-dependent kinases.
CYCc	Adenylyl- / guanylyl cyclase, catalytic domain	SM00044	Present in two copies in mammalian adenylyl cyclases. Eubacterial homologues are known. Two residues (Asn, Arg) are thought to be involved in catalysis. These cyclases have important roles in a diverse range of cellular processes.
Cyclin_C	N/A	SM01332	Cyclins are a family of proteins that control the progression of cells through the cell cycle by activating cyclin-dependent kinase (Cdk) enzymes.
Cyt-b5	Cytochrome b5-like Heme/Steroid binding domain	SM01117	This family includes heme binding domains from a diverse range of proteins. This family also includes proteins that bind to steroids. The family includes progesterone receptors such as O00264 ((PUBMED:9705155),(PUBMED:8774719)). Many members of this subfamily are membrane anchored by an N-terminal transmembrane alpha helix. This family also includes a domain in some chitin synthases. There is no known ligand for this domain in the chitin synthases.
DAGKa	Diacylglycerol kinase accessory domain (presumed)	SM00045	Diacylglycerol (DAG) is a second messenger that acts as a protein kinase C activator. DAG can be produced from the hydrolysis of phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) by a phosphoinositide-specific phospholipase C and by the degradation of phosphatidylcholine (PC) by a phospholipase C or the concerted actions of phospholipase D and phosphatidate phosphohydrolase. This domain might either be an accessory domain or else contribute to the catalytic domain. Bacterial homologues are known.

DAX	Domain present in Dishevelled and axin	SM00021	Domain of unknown function.
DEATH	domain, found in proteins involved in cell death (apoptosis).	SM00005	Alpha-helical domain present in a variety of proteins with apoptotic functions. Some (but not all) of these domains form homotypic and heterotypic dimers.
DEP	Domain found in Dishevelled, Egl-10, and Pleckstrin	SM00049	Domain of unknown function present in signalling proteins that contain PH, rasGEF, rhoGEF, rhoGAP, RGS, PDZ domains. DYNc	Dynamin, GTPase	SM00053	Large GTPases that mediate vesicle trafficking. Dynamin participates in the endocytic uptake of receptors, associated ligands, and plasma membrane following an exocytic event.
EAL	Putative diguanylate phosphodiesterase	SM00052	Putative diguanylate phosphodiesterase, present in a variety of bacteria.
EFh	EF-hand, calcium binding motif	SM00054	EF-hands are calcium-binding motifs that occur at least in pairs. Links between disease states and genes encoding EF-hands, particularly the S100 subclass, are emerging. Each motif consists of a 12 residue loop flanked on either side by a 12 residue alpha-helix. EF-hands undergo a conformational change unpon binding calcium ions.
EH	Eps15 homology domain	SM00027	Pair of EF hand motifs that recognise proteins containing Asn-Pro-Phe (NPF) sequences.
FCH	Fes/CIP4 homology domain	SM00055	Alignment extended from original report. Highly alpha-helical. Also known as the RAEYL motif or the S. pombe Cdc15 N-terminal domain.
FF	Contains two conserved F residues	SM00441	A novel motif that often accompanies WW domains. Often contains two conserved Phe (F) residues.
FH2	Formin Homology 2 Domain	SM00498	FH proteins control rearrangements of the actin cytoskeleton, especially in the context of cytokinesis and cell polarisation. Members of this family have been found to interact with Rho-GTPases, profilin and other actin-assoziated proteins. These interactions are mediated by the proline-rich FH1 domain, usually located in front of FH2 (but not listed in SMART). Despite this cytosolic function, vertebrate formins have been assigned functions within the nucleus. A set of Formin-Binding Proteins (FBPs) has been shown to bind FH1 with their WW domain.
FHA	Forkhead associated domain	SM00240	Found in eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins. Putative nuclear signalling domain.
FIST	N domain	SM00897	The FIST N domain is a novel sensory domain, which is present in signal transduction proteins from Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya. Chromosomal proximity of FIST-encoding genes to those coding for proteins involved in amino acid metabolism and transport suggest that FIST domains bind small ligands, such as amino acids.
Frizzled	/Smoothened family membrane region	SM01330	Frizzled is a family of G protein-coupled receptor proteins (PMID: 14977528) that serves as receptors in the Wnt signaling pathway and other signaling pathways. When activated, Frizzled leads to activation of Dishevelled in the cytosol.
FYVE	Protein present in Fab1, YOTB, Vac1, and EEA1	SM00064	The FYVE zinc finger is named after four proteins where it was first found: Fab1, YOTB/ZK632.12, Vac1, and EEA1. The FYVE finger has been shown to bind two Zn2+ ions. The FYVE finger has eight potential zinc coordinating cysteine positions. The FYVE finger is structurally related to the PHD finger and the RING finger. Many members of this family also include two histidines in a motif R+HHC+XCG, where + represents a charged residue and X any residue. The FYVE finger functions in the membrane recruitment of cytosolic proteins by binding to phosphatidylinositol 3-phosphate (PI3P), which is prominent on endosomes. The R+HHC+XCG motif is critical for PI3P binding.
G_alpha	G protein alpha subunit	SM00275	Subunit of G proteins that contains the guanine nucleotide binding site
GAF	Domain present in phytochromes and cGMP-specific phosphodiesterases.	SM00065	Mutations within these domains in PDE6B result in autosomal recessive inheritance of retinitis pigmentosa.
GAS2	Growth-Arrest-Specific Protein 2 Domain	SM00243	GROWTH-ARREST-SPECIFIC PROTEIN 2 Domain
GGDEF	diguanylate cyclase	SM00267	Diguanylate cyclase, present in a variety of bacteria.
GoLoco	LGN motif, putative GEFs specific for G-alpha GTPases	SM00390	GEF specific for Galpha_i proteins
GS	motif	SM00467	Aa approx. 30 amino acid motif that precedes the kinase domain in types I and II TGF beta receptors. Mutation of two or more of the serines or threonines in the TTSGSGSG of TGF-beta type I receptor impairs phosphorylation and signaling activity.
GuKc	Guanylate kinase homologues.	SM00072	Active enzymes catalyze ATP-dependent phosphorylation of GMP to GDP. Structure resembles that of adenylate kinase. So-called membrane-associated guanylate kinase homologues (MAGUKs) do not possess guanylate kinase activities; instead at least some possess protein-binding functions.
HATPase_c	Histidine kinase-like ATPases	SM00387	Histidine kinase-, DNA gyrase B-, phytochrome-like ATPases.
HECTc	Domain Homologous to E6-AP Carboxyl Terminus with	SM00119	E3 ubiquitin-protein ligases. Can bind to E2 enzymes.
HisKA	His Kinase A (phosphoacceptor) domain	SM00388	Dimerisation and phosphoacceptor domain of histidine kinases.
HPT	Histidine Phosphotransfer domain	SM00073	Contains an active histidine residue that mediates phosphotransfer reactions. Domain detected only in eubacteria. This alignment is an extension to that shown in the Cell structure paper.
Hr1	Rho effector or protein kinase C-related kinase homology region 1 homologues	SM00742	Alpha-helical domain found in vertebrate PRK1 and yeast PKC1 protein kinases C. The HR1 in rhophilin bind RhoGTP; those in PRK1 bind RhoA and RhoB. Also called RBD - Rho-binding domain
ILWEQ	I/LWEQ domain	SM00307	Thought to possess an F-actin binding function.
